article.description:
The Bulls rallied from a 14-point fourth-quarter deficit and
finished the game with a 16-0 run Saturday night, capping a 118-111
victory that snapped an 11-game losing streak on the Wizards' home
floor.
article.headline: Bulls finish with 16-0 run, close out Wizards
article.linkText: Bulls finish game with 16-0 run, close out Wizards
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Over three years, the Chicago Bulls had become all too familiar with celebrations at the MCI Center. This time, the Washington Wizards started reveling a bit too soon and were dealt a stunning defeat, one made even more painful by the sight of Gilbert Arenas limping off the court. The Bulls rallied from a 14-point fourth-quarter deficit and finished the game with a 16-0 run Saturday night, capping a 118-111 victory that snapped an 11-game losing streak on the Wizards' home floor. "It seemed like everything they did was going their way," said Luol Deng, who had 21 points and a career-high 12 rebounds in his first start of the season. "They were quicker to loose balls and getting out and getting easy dunks and stuff. We just felt like they were celebrating and thinking the game was over. We turned it around, started competing and we were able to get back in it." Chris Duhon scored all of his 24 points in the second half. Kirk Hinrich had 22 points, 13 assists and seven rebounds, and Darius Songalia scored eight of his season-high 15 points in the fourth quarter for the Bulls, who trailed by nine with 3 minutes to play. The game was the first meeting between the teams since the first round of last season's playoffs, when the Wizards won the final four games -- including three at home -- to take the series 4-2. The victory moved the Bulls back above .500, although they remain in last place in the Central Division. "It feels good to win over here," Hinrich said. "We desperately needed a win." Arenas scored 42 points for the Wizards, but he committed nine turnovers and was injured and disgruntled after three consecutive calls went against him in the final minutes. He was whistled for a charge and a defensive foul and then was unhappy with a no-call when he crashed to the floor after his shot was blocked by Songalia. Arenas then sat in front of the scorer's table in what looked like a protest, but he said he was trying to shake off cobwebs. Official Joe Crawford told Arenas to get up, then Arenas limped to the bench and was replaced after a free throw. "I was dizzy," Arenas said. "So I was just trying to sit. Hopefully there were going to let me sit there for a while." Arenas said his "whole right side" is aching from a big bruise, an aggravation of back soreness he was already experiencing. He said he would try to play Sunday against first-place Miami. "I don't want to let a little stupid back injury hurt and disappoint my team," he said. As for the calls that went against him, Arenas made comments that were more restrained that they might have been in his more temperamental past. "As a professional, we get upset sometimes," Arenas said. "We get to yelling at the ref. Sometimes if there's a call there and they don't want to see it, they don't want to see it." Meanwhile, Antawn Jamison was frustrated by the Wizards' defense, which has been lacking all season. The Wizards have lost nine of 12, and they've blown a big lead in back-to-back games. "It's an embarrassment to play that way, four or five minutes to go and lose a 12-point lead," said Jamison, who had 16 points and 12 rebounds. "I give you a 100 percent guarantee. I'm going to find a way to motivate these guys. Maybe I have to whoop and holler every game. Maybe I have to get more emotional." The game's other subplot was Tyson Chandler, who came off the bench for the first time this season. Chandler has been undergoing tests to determine the cause of chronic fatigue, and he had one point and five rebounds in 28 minutes in a loss to the Los Angeles Lakers on Friday night. Chandler had four points, five rebounds and five fouls in 24 minutes on Saturday, and he badly all three of his free throws. "I actually felt a little better. I was moving around a little better and my wind was a little stronger out there," Chandler said. "I'm just hoping this is a good sign and I'm moving in the right direction. The way I've been playing, I can't blame my coach (for not starting me). I've been not giving my team enough and I've been questioning my health."

Game notes
A pair of guards who couldn't get off their team's bench the last two games were back in action. Washington's Chucky Atkins went 0-for-3 in 10 minutes, and Chicago's Eric Piatkowski scored four points 12 minutes. ... Wizards F Michael Ruffin returned after missing four games with right knee tendinitis. ... It was throwback night at MCI Center, with the Wizards wearing the bizarre orange and blue uniforms of the 1972-73 Baltimore Bullets. The Bulls looked more conventional in their Chicago Stags uniforms from the late 1940s.
